    text: `He really was an impossible person. Too shy altogether. With absolutely nothing to say for himself. And such a weight. Once he was in your studio he never knew when to go, but would sit on and on until you nearly screamed, and burned to throw something enormous after him when he did finally blush his way out—something like the tortoise stove. The strange thing was that at first sight he looked most interesting. Everybody agreed about that. You would drift into the cafe one evening and there you would see, sitting in a corner, with a glass of coffee in front of him, a thin, dark boy, with a blue ring on his finger and a faint flush of red on his cheeks. He attracted you at once—just as a beautiful moth might—but then, when you went closer, you found that he was just a case for the entomologist. Only the moth was not so silent, nor so obsessed with that one thing—whatever it was that held him.

When questioned about his work Ian said very little. 'I am trying to paint,' he would murmur, blushing. It was all very well for anyone to say that he was an impossible person. But the curious thing was that nobody could be more certain of that than he was himself. He knew he was impossible. Deep down, he had a kind of hopeless adoration for the young women who passed by his studio, but he could never think of anything to say to them.

He lived in a studio high up on a hill, overlooking the roofs of the old town. In the evening, leaning out of his window, he could see the lights come out in the houses below. Down the street a funny old man came trundling a piano organ. The sounds of the waltz rose up to him, grew fuller and richer, then faded away. He saw a girl come flying down the street to meet the old man. She looked up at the sound, and Ian saw her laugh. Perhaps it was the waltz, perhaps the evening, perhaps the girl—but Ian French felt, for the first time in his life, a strange and painful excitement. He leaned further out of the window, his heart beating fast. Something was happening to him. He did not know what it was. But he felt it.

The girl across the street was about sixteen, with dark hair, and she wore a red dress. She lived with an old woman who was probably her grandmother. Every morning at a certain hour, she opened the shutters of the window opposite and leaned out. She was always alone. And Ian, who had never been able to stir from his studio, found himself waiting for that moment, standing just inside his own dark room, watching. Once he nearly waved to her, but his hand stopped, frozen at his side.

There came a day, a Thursday, when he could bear it no longer. He rushed out of his studio, down the stairs, and stood in the street, looking up. But the window was blank. The shutters were closed. He waited until the evening, and then the next morning, and the next. But she did not appear. He never saw her again.`
